awd_titl_txt: Refining a Model with Tools to Develop Math PD Leaders: An Implementation Study
awd_abstract_narration:
There is increased demand for K-12 teacher professional development that yields improvements in student learning and achievement. This need is particularly high given widespread adoption of the Common Core State Standards (CCSS) in mathematics which challenges teachers to incorporate mathematical thinking and problem solving into their instruction. The professional development challenge is exacerbated as our nation's demographics continue to shift, increasing the number of English language learners in school districts throughout the U.S. To meet this demand, the educational community must develop large-scale, system-level professional development programs aligned with the CCSS that are scalable and sustainable. The project team from Stanford University will work with middle school mathematics teachers in San Francisco Unified School District to develop their capacity to conduct professional development for the teachers in their schools. A central goal of this project is to develop models and resources for effective professional development and preparation of professional development leaders in mathematics with special attention to students who are English language learners. These models and resources will: provide school districts with the tools to build local capacity and provide sustainable professional development to all middle school mathematics teachers; improve the quality of teaching and, in turn, make important progress toward ensuring that all students in middle school can achieve the mathematical skills and understandings identified in the new standards; and meet the needs of English language learners. In addition, the Stanford team will contribute to the knowledge base in mathematics education, professional development and English language learners.

In previous work, the team developed two interconnected models--the Problem-Solving Cycle (PSC) and the Mathematics Leadership Preparation (MLP) models for preparing professional development leaders. The PSC model consists of a series of interconnected workshops organized around a problem that can be solved using multiple representations and solutions and can be adapted for multiple grade levels. Each cycle focuses on a different math problem. During the first cycle, teachers collaboratively solve the focal math problem and develop plans for teaching it to their students. Teachers then teach the lesson in their classes and the lessons are videotaped. Subsequent workshops focus on participants' classroom experiences teaching the problem. The goals of these workshops are to help teachers learn how to build on student thinking and to explore a variety of instructional practices. They rely heavily on video clips from the PSC lesson to foster productive conversations and situate the conversations in teachers' classroom instruction. The MLP model is designed to prepare Math Leaders to facilitate the PSC. The MLP prepares teachers to lead professional development for their colleagues. These models showed promise of effectiveness in improving middle school mathematics teachers' knowledge and practice, developing math professional development leaders, and improving student achievement. Investigators intend to refine and test the design of the PSC and MLP models and develop resources that can be used by other schools and districts, as well as conduct an evaluation of the work.

por.por_cntn:
The primary goals of this project were to 1) refine two professional learning models -- one to support site-based Teacher Leaders in conducting professional learning for middle school mathematics teachers and one to support district mathematics professional development (PD) coordinators in their work to prepare teacher leaders; 2) develop a set of digital resources, including resources for district PD coordinators and an online Facilitator's Guide to support Teacher Leaders in conducting professional learning and adapting key ideas from the models to their local teacher and student populations and organizational and policy contexts; 3) assess the effectiveness of the refined models and resources for enhancing teachers' instructional practices; and 4) develop district capacity to sustain instructional improvement for middle school mathematics teachers and teacher leaders.

Key Outcomes related to these goals include the following:

1. Refinement of the Models

The first phase of the research identified two overarching categories of adaptations that we used to refine the models to better support the district goals. We made adaptations that incorporated the district curriculum, addressed the needs of English learners, integrated the teacher leaders' learning of the professional learning model into the leadership preparation model, increased the emphasis on what it means to be an instructional leader, scaffolded the teacher leaders' selection of video clips, and incorporated the use of rehearsals and debriefing activities to support leadership development.
por.por_txt_cntn:
The primary goals of this project were to 1) refine two professional learning models -- one to support site-based Teacher Leaders in conducting professional learning for middle school mathematics teachers and one to support district mathematics professional development (PD) coordinators in their work to prepare teacher leaders; 2) develop a set of digital resources, including resources for district PD coordinators and an online Facilitator's Guide to support Teacher Leaders in conducting professional learning and adapting key ideas from the models to their local teacher and student populations and organizational and policy contexts; 3) assess the effectiveness of the refined models and resources for enhancing teachers' instructional practices; and 4) develop district capacity to sustain instructional improvement for middle school mathematics teachers and teacher leaders.

Key Outcomes related to these goals include the following:

1. Refinement of the Models

The first phase of the research identified two overarching categories of adaptations that we used to refine the models to better support the district goals. We made adaptations that incorporated the district curriculum, addressed the needs of English learners, integrated the teacher leaders' learning of the professional learning model into the leadership preparation model, increased the emphasis on what it means to be an instructional leader, scaffolded the teacher leaders' selection of video clips, and incorporated the use of rehearsals and debriefing activities to support leadership development.



The implications of this work illustrate the need for researchers to be responsive to the context of their school partners if they expect their work to be meaningful and sustainable. Using the frame of design-based implementation research proved to be an effective strategy for working with the district STEM leadership team and site-based teacher leaders to adapt the models to support district implementation of a new curriculum that necessitates shifts in teacher practices, and for determining how to make video-based discussions more productive activities in the models.

2. Digital Resources  

The resources for teacher leaders and district leaders can be found here: https://cset.stanford.edu/problem-solving-cycle-and-teacher-leadership-preparation

3. Teachers' Instructional Practices

Students with agency and authority in the classroom learn more so we studied teachers' discourse during professional development focused on agency and authority in middle school mathematics classrooms. We found that teachers frequently engaged with ideas related to student agency and authority. Though less common, there were also episodes in which teachers constructed new ideas and critiqued existing ones. These findings indicate that using activity prompts, practicing responsive facilitation, normalizing critical stances, and positioning frameworks as tentative are important strategies for supporting teachers' deeper engagement with ideas related to student agency and authority. This study provides preliminary evidence that school-based workshops facilitated by novice teacher leaders are a viable means of supporting teachers' engagement with ideas about agency and authority.

4. District Capacity Development

In an examination of data gathered over 3 years, we see that Teacher Leaders regularly used the key structures of the professional learning model; made adaptations in response to their school goals, interests, and priorities; and gained confidence in their work with colleagues. Specifically, we saw a number of key changes that indicated their growth as leaders of professional learning:

●      Teacher leader participation within teams balanced out over time instead of being dominated by an individual

●      During leadership preparation sessions, teacher leaders took more initiative and asked more questions

●      Teacher leaders began rehearsing facilitation moves with their colleagues instead of describing what they would do in their professional learning workshops

Beyond individual growth of teacher leaders, other common patterns in our data underscored that the practices that support professional development were compromised when allocated time was taken away from leadership preparation sessions such that planning time was curtailed, or school-based workshops were shortened and critical elements that supported teacher growth could not be included.

Intellectual Merit

As evidenced from the findings above, this project has expanded the research on effective ways to work in a research-practice partnership to create capacity for teacher leadership in service of instructional improvement for the teaching of mathematics.

Broader Impacts

Looking across all the findings of this project, the impact of our work is to reinforce the value of time for professional learning if we want teachers to grow and improve during their careers. Professional learning is essential for all types of professions, but educators in public schools are often overlooked and rarely provided with the quantity and quality of time and resources to be able to grow and improve over time as a part of their professional work day.
